Basemap¶

Basemap is a library for plotting 2D data on maps in Python. You can find documentation on Basemap at the following sites: (official documention here, unofficial documentation here )

To install it, open your terminal and run:

conda install basemap

If this doesn't work then you can you use conda forge basemap, and conda forge basemap-data-hires and follow the directions.

In [38]:
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt 
import warnings
from mpl_toolkits.basemap import Basemap
warnings.filterwarnings("ignore")
%matplotlib inline

To draw our first map, we simply do the following:

In [39]:
map = Basemap()
map.drawcoastlines()
Out[39]:
<matplotlib.collections.LineCollection at 0x1fdd0ee1390>

The default projection is the Equirectangular projection but you can change it to another projection:

In [40]:
map = Basemap(projection='ortho', lat_0=0, lon_0=0)
map.drawcoastlines()
Out[40]:
<matplotlib.collections.LineCollection at 0x1fdd1758d68>

lat_0 and lon_0 sets the center of the map. Changing it allows us to see the other parts of the earth.

In [41]:
map = Basemap(projection='ortho', lat_0=0, lon_0=90)
map.drawcoastlines()
Out[41]:
<matplotlib.collections.LineCollection at 0x1fdd1471d68>

To fill in the continents and oceans with some colors you can do the following:

In [42]:
map = Basemap(projection='ortho', lat_0=0, lon_0=0)
map.drawmapboundary(fill_color='aqua')
map.fillcontinents(color='coral',lake_color='aqua')
map.drawcoastlines()
Out[42]:
<matplotlib.collections.LineCollection at 0x1fdd176a978>

You can add country lines as well:

In [43]:
map = Basemap(projection='ortho', lat_0=0, lon_0=0)
map.drawmapboundary(fill_color='aqua')
map.fillcontinents(color='coral',lake_color='aqua')
map.drawcoastlines()
map.drawcountries()
Out[43]:
<matplotlib.collections.LineCollection at 0x1fdd1250e10>

The map is essentially a matplotlib object, so you can use matplotlib's methods to access it. For example, to draw some points on the map you can use the following:

In [44]:
map = Basemap(projection='ortho', lat_0=0, lon_0=-30)
map.drawmapboundary(fill_color='aqua')
map.fillcontinents(color='coral',lake_color='aqua')
map.drawcoastlines()
x, y = map(-10, 0) #x=longitude, y=latitude
map.plot(x, y, marker='D',color='m')
Out[44]:
[<matplotlib.lines.Line2D at 0x1fdd16e5b38>]

You can add text and label a city by using the text function.

In [45]:
map = Basemap(projection='ortho', 
              lat_0=0, lon_0=0)

map.drawmapboundary(fill_color='dodgerblue')
map.fillcontinents(color='orange',lake_color='dodgerblue')
map.drawcoastlines()

lon = 3.4
lat = 3.4

x, y = map(lon, lat)

plt.text(x, y, 'Lagos',fontsize=12,fontweight='bold',
                    ha='left',va='bottom',color='k')

plt.show()
In [46]:
map = Basemap(llcrnrlon=-10.5,llcrnrlat=35,urcrnrlon=4.,urcrnrlat=44.,
             resolution='i', projection='tmerc', lat_0 = 39.5, lon_0 = -3.25)

map.drawmapboundary(fill_color='dodgerblue')
map.fillcontinents(color='orange',lake_color='dodgerblue')
map.drawcoastlines()
lon = -3.25
lat = 39.5

x, y = map(lon, lat)
plt.text(x, y, 'Quero, Spain',fontsize=10,fontweight='bold',
                    ha='center',va='center',color='k')
map.plot(x, y, marker='D',color='r')

plt.show()

There are a few different options for adding more detailed topography to the Earth's surface on your map. You can create a map using NASA's blue marble model.

In [47]:
m = Basemap(width=12000000,height=9000000,projection='lcc',
            resolution=None,lat_1=45.,lat_2=55,lat_0=50,lon_0=-107.)
m.bluemarble()
plt.show()

You can also create a shaded relief map

In [48]:
m = Basemap(width=12000000,height=9000000,projection='lcc',
            resolution=None,lat_1=45.,lat_2=55,lat_0=50,lon_0=-107.)
m.shadedrelief()
plt.show()

or you can create an etopo relief map

In [49]:
m = Basemap(width=12000000,height=9000000,projection='lcc',
            resolution=None,lat_1=45.,lat_2=55,lat_0=50,lon_0=-107.)
m.etopo()
plt.show()
